The full X25519 Montgomery ladder as a recursive callable, Brick 3 of
docs/x25519-design.md — the centerpiece that loops where the let-chain
unroll cannot.

`ladder` recurses 255 times over a single LadderState record (the four
working coordinates x2,z2,x3,z3 + the base x1, 10 limbs each, plus swap,
the bit counter i, the output selector which, and the 64-char hex
scalar text). At each level it:
  - extracts the clamped scalar bit at index i-1 (byte_at into the hex
    scalar, decode 2 hex chars, shift+mask; RFC 7748 clamp folded in:
    bits 0..2 forced 0, bit 254 forced 1);
  - branch-free cswap of (x2,x3) and (z2,z3) on swap xor bit;
  - one differential add-and-double (the Brick-2 step), inlined;
  - recurses with i-1.
At i==0 it does the final cswap and returns limb `which` (0..19) of the
final (x2,z2).

Termination is mechanical: `decreasing : i` over i : number [0,255].
This is the first Verbose program to thread ~51 number fields plus a
text field through 255 recursive frames (the wide ABI de-risked by the
S2 spike). Validated end-to-end against RFC 7748 section 5.2 vector 1:
the native ladder's final (x2,z2), after modular inversion and
encoding, reproduces the published shared secret exactly. The integration
test pins several output limbs against the RFC-derived reference.

Still done outside Verbose for this brick: the final z2^(p-2) inversion
and the byte encoding (Brick 4 brings those in-language).
